        "timestamp": "2017-12-01 16:49:40.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1: -Code-Review\n\n> (11 comments)\n\nL144: It installs and runs.  Wouldn't that indicate that it has all of the dependencies that it needs?\n\nL88: Is it ok to subclass from RuntimeException, or will sonar complain about that, too?\n\nL838: Is it sufficient to simply add a comment to an empty block of code?  Or does sonar require the block to actually contain an executable line of code in every block?",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "6c7546ac29102ae707cecfd080c8b72e301bc22c",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 477,
          "name": "Jorge Hernandez",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "jorge.hernandez-herrero@att.com",
          "username": "jhh"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2017-12-01 17:25:22.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nL144 - yes, it is good\nL88 - you can use and existing subclass if it fits the purpose, for example a commonly used one is IllegalArgumentException or create a custom one for your semantics.\nL838 - sonar requires to log exceptions, passing explicitly \"e\" to the logger, or rethrow them.   You could set the logging statement if you don't care to trace or debug, just to satisfy sonar.  alternative is to mark it as false positive but that requires manual maintenance",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "82b8ac0e5dd4d547f0190b40e2a6b2f2c6fa17c0",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 811,
          "name": "Jim Hahn",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "jrh3@att.com",
          "username": "jrh3"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2017-12-01 17:48:36.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n> L144 - yes, it is good\n > L88 - you can use and existing subclass if it fits the purpose, for\n > example a commonly used one is IllegalArgumentException or create a\n > custom one for your semantics.\n > L838 - sonar requires to log exceptions, passing explicitly \"e\" to\n > the logger, or rethrow them.   You could set the logging statement\n > if you don't care to trace or debug, just to satisfy sonar. \n > alternative is to mark it as false positive but that requires\n > manual maintenance\n\nL838: Is this true even within junit tests?  Seems like this particular complaint (and the one about generic exceptions) should be disabled for junit test code, as they require extra code that is of dubious value.",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
